<!-- ═══════════════════ GLOSSARY ════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="glossary">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-tag">Reference</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">Temple Glossary</h2>
      <p class="section-subtitle">Key terms from Sanskrit, Agamic tradition, and architectural history.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="glossary-grid">
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Agama</span><span class="glossary-def">Sacred texts governing temple construction, ritual, and theology. Over 200 Agamas exist for different deity traditions.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Amalaka</span><span class="glossary-def">The ribbed, disc-like stone element crowning the Nagara shikhara, just below the kalasha.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Antarala</span><span class="glossary-def">The vestibule or antechamber connecting the garbhagriha to the mandapa.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Ardha Mandapa</span><span class="glossary-def">The half-hall or portico at the entrance of a temple, before the main mandapa.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Bahiṣkāra</span><span class="glossary-def">Ritual exclusion — the formal process by which a desecrated temple is declared ritually impure.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Brahmasthana</span><span class="glossary-def">The central point of the Vastu Purusha Mandala — the cosmic center, left empty or occupied by the primary deity's placement.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Devadasi</span><span class="glossary-def">Women dedicated to temple service — historically performing music, dance, and ritual functions as part of the temple's cultural life.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Dhvajastambha</span><span class="glossary-def">The flagstaff or pillar bearing the temple flag, positioned along the main axis between the entrance and the main shrine.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Garbhagriha</span><span class="glossary-def">The innermost sanctum — literally "womb-house." The dark, sacred space housing the primary murti.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Gopuram</span><span class="glossary-def">The monumental gateway towers of Dravidian temples. The word derives from "gopa" (cow-pen gateway) — an architectural ascent from the utilitarian to the divine.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Jyotirlinga</span><span class="glossary-def">One of the 12 self-manifested Shivalingams of divine light — the most sacred Shaiva pilgrimage sites.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Kalasha</span><span class="glossary-def">The finial pot atop a temple tower. Filled with sacred materials and ritually installed during the Kumbhabhisheka ceremony.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Kumbhabhisheka</span><span class="glossary-def">The great consecration ceremony — performed at a temple's founding and renewed periodically. Involves the ritual installation of the kalasha and reconsecration of the deity.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Mahamandapa</span><span class="glossary-def">The great hall — the largest assembly space within a temple complex, used for festivals, performances, and large gatherings.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Mandapa</span><span class="glossary-def">The pillared hall(s) of a temple. May include multiple mandapas — nritta-mandapa (dance), sabha-mandapa (assembly), kalyana-mandapa (marriage).</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Murti</span><span class="glossary-def">The sacred image or form of a deity, consecrated through Prana Pratishtha to become a living divine presence.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Pancharatha</span><span class="glossary-def">A temple plan with five projections (ratha = chariot) on each wall face, creating a complex star-like ground plan.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Prakara</span><span class="glossary-def">The enclosure wall surrounding a temple complex. Major temples may have multiple concentric prakaras.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Prana Pratishtha</span><span class="glossary-def">The ritual installation of life-force into a murti — the ceremony by which an idol becomes a living divine presence.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Pradakshina</span><span class="glossary-def">Ritual clockwise circumambulation of the deity or temple. The path is the pradakshina-patha.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Pushkarini</span><span class="glossary-def">The sacred temple tank used for ritual bathing and water management. Often elaborately stepped.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Rekha Prasada</span><span class="glossary-def">The basic Nagara shikhara form — a single curvilinear tower. The foundational element of North Indian temple towers.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Shakti Peetha</span><span class="glossary-def">One of the 51 sacred seats of Goddess Shakti across the subcontinent — sites where Sati's body parts fell.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Shikhara</span><span class="glossary-def">The tower above the garbhagriha in Nagara temples. The curvilinear mountain-peak form rising towards the sky.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Sthapati</span><span class="glossary-def">The chief temple architect — a hereditary specialist in Agamic temple construction. The Sthapati must be both technically expert and ritually pure.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Tālamāna</span><span class="glossary-def">The system of proportional measurement used in temple construction — linking architectural dimensions to human body proportions and astronomical units.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Utsava Murti</span><span class="glossary-def">The processional idol of a temple — taken out during festivals and processions. Distinct from the fixed moola murti in the garbhagriha.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Vastu Purusha Mandala</span><span class="glossary-def">The sacred geometric grid underlying all Hindu temple design — encoding cosmic, anatomical, and astronomical knowledge in a unified spatial system.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Vimana</span><span class="glossary-def">In South Indian architecture — the tower directly above the garbhagriha (pyramidal, stepped form). In North Indian usage, sometimes refers to the entire shrine.</span></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══════════════════ FAQ ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="faq">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-tag">Common Questions</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <p class="section-subtitle">Answered with honesty — clearly separating scriptural tradition, historical evidence, and modern scholarship.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)">
          Why do Hindu temples have erotic sculpture (as at Khajuraho)?
          <span class="faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-a">
          <p>The erotic imagery at Khajuraho and Konark has multiple scholarly interpretations. The most academically supported: these images represent the full spectrum of human experience (the kama aspect of Purushartha — the four goals of life: dharma, artha, kama, moksha). They appear on the <em>outer walls</em> — the threshold between the world and the sacred — not inside the sanctum.</p>
          <p>The Tantric interpretation holds that the mithuna (divine couple) imagery represents the union of Shiva and Shakti — the cosmic masculine and feminine principles whose union generates the universe. Entering the temple means moving from kama (desire, the outer world) toward moksha (liberation, the inner sanctum). The erotic imagery is the outer wall's statement; the inner sanctum's statement is transcendence.</p>
          <p>The auspiciousness interpretation is also documented: divine couples were considered protective, and their imagery was placed at entrances to ward off malevolent forces.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)">
          Were Hindu temples really wealthy economic centers?
          <span class="faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-a">
          <p>Yes — extensively documented by temple inscriptions. The Brihadeeswarar's own inscriptions record that Rajaraja Chola assigned the revenues of over 80 villages to support the temple. The Tirupati Balaji temple today is the richest religious institution in the world by annual income (₹3,000+ crore/year).</p>
          <p>Major temples were economic nodes: they employed hundreds to thousands of people (priests, cooks, gardeners, musicians, dancers, accountants, guards, craftsmen), held large agricultural land grants, managed irrigation systems, ran educational institutions (pathashalas), and dispensed food and medicine. They were simultaneously sanctuary, university, hospital, treasury, and cultural center.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)">
          How many Hindu temples were destroyed by medieval Islamic rulers?
          <span class="faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-a">
          <p>This is a historically sensitive question that requires careful separation of verified evidence from partisan claims. What is <strong>historically documented</strong>:</p>
          <p>Historian Richard Eaton, in his landmark work "Temple Desecration and Muslim States in Medieval India" (2000), documents approximately <strong>80 episodes</strong> of verifiable temple destruction by Muslim rulers between 1000 and 1760 CE, based on primary sources. Eaton notes that contemporary Persian chronicles (the Tabaqat-i-Nasiri, Muntakhab-ut-Tawarikh, Tarikh-i-Firuzshahi, etc.) <em>themselves</em> proudly record these destructions as acts of Islamic piety.</p>
          <p>However, the claim of "30,000" or "60,000" temples destroyed (often cited) has no reliable archaeological or textual basis — these figures are not verifiable. The verified documented cases of major temple destruction run into the dozens to low hundreds. The human, cultural, and civilizational loss was nevertheless catastrophic and irreversible for thousands of communities.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)">
          What is the scientific basis for "temple energy"?
          <span class="faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-a">
          <p>This question mixes verified facts with speculative claims. <strong>What is verified:</strong> Several temple sites have been found to be located above geological features associated with higher-than-average geomagnetic fields. The specific stone types used in some garbhagrihas (especially certain granites) have magnetic properties. The acoustic properties of some temple halls are measurably different from ambient environments.</p>
          <p><strong>What is speculative:</strong> Claims of specific "energy healing," dramatic electromagnetic effects, or conscious design of "pyramid power" effects are not scientifically verified. The practices of removing footwear (reduces static electricity), metal bell-ringing (acoustic stimulation), camphor burning (respiratory effects of specific terpenes), and circumambulation (moderate aerobic activity) all have physiological effects — but attributing these to "temple energy" specifically is a cultural interpretation, not a measured scientific phenomenon.</p>
          <p>The honest position: temple design incorporates intuitive knowledge of acoustics, light, and geometry that deserves serious scientific study — and some of that study is now beginning to happen. Sensational claims without evidence should be distinguished from genuine scientific inquiry.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)">
          What are the 64 types of temples described in the Manasara?
          <span class="faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-a">
          <p>The <em>Manasara</em> (an ancient treatise on architecture, c. 5th–7th century CE) describes 64 types of temple plans based on the number of squares in the Vastu Purusha Mandala grid and the number of wall projections (rathas). The classification ranges from the simplest <strong>Eka-anga</strong> (single-space, 1×1 plan) to the most complex multi-ratha plans.</p>
          <p>The key classification system is by the number of projecting "chariot" elements (rathas) on the wall face: Triratha (3), Pancharatha (5), Saptaratha (7), Navaratha (9), etc. Each additional ratha increases the complexity of the plan and, correspondingly, the complexity of the shikhara's silhouette above it. The entire North Indian temple tradition can be taxonomized using this ratha system.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFAQ(this)">
          What is the Gyanvapi controversy, and what does history say?
          <span class="faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-a">
          <p>The Gyanvapi Mosque in Varanasi was built adjacent to (and partially on the site of) the original Kashi Vishwanath temple, which was demolished by Aurangzeb in 1669 CE. The demolition order is documented in a Mughal farman (royal decree) and in official Mughal chronicles including the Maasir-i-Alamgiri.</p>
          <p>The western wall of the original temple — visible within the Gyanvapi compound — shows clearly Hindu architectural elements (pillar bases, carvings). Recent court-ordered ASI (Archaeological Survey of India) surveys in 2023 found extensive evidence of a Hindu temple predating the mosque, including artistic and architectural elements.</p>
          <p>The legal status is under determination by Indian courts. The historical fact of the destruction of the original temple is not disputed by serious historians; the legal and political path forward is contested and ongoing.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══════════════════ FINAL ENCYCLOPEDIA ══════════════════ -->
<section style="background: var(--bg-primary); padding: 6rem 2rem;">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-tag">Master Index</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">Encyclopedia Summary</h2>
      <p class="section-subtitle">A beginner's quick-reference guide to Hindu temples, their traditions, and their civilizational significance.</p>
    </div>

    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 3rem; margin-bottom: 4rem;">
      <div class="intro-text reveal">
        <h3>For the First-Time Pilgrim</h3>
        <p>When you enter a Hindu temple, you are entering a <em>microcosm of the universe</em>. The journey from the gopuram (gate) to the garbhagriha (sanctum) is a journey from the periphery of consciousness to its center — from diversity to the singular divine reality.</p>
        <p>The correct approach is with <em>bhava</em> — a feeling of devotion, openness, and presence. Remove footwear at the threshold. Move clockwise (pradakshina). The darkness of the garbhagriha is intentional — the divine is found in the innermost, quietest place, not in spectacle.</p>
        <div class="highlight-box">
          <strong>Remember:</strong> You are not visiting a museum. A temple with Prana Pratishtha is a living being. The deity is considered present, aware, and responsive to sincere prayer.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="intro-text reveal">
        <h3>For the Scholar & Researcher</h3>
        <p>Hindu temple studies is a rich interdisciplinary field drawing on: Sanskrit epigraphy, archaeology, art history, religious studies, anthropology, acoustics, astronomy, and mathematics. The primary sources — Agamas, Vastu texts, Puranas, inscriptions — are extensive and largely untranslated.</p>
        <p>Key research institutions: Archaeological Survey of India (ASI), French Institute of Pondicherry (École Française d'Extrême-Orient — EFEO), American Institute of Indian Studies (AIIS), Indira Gandhi National Centre for the Arts (IGNCA), and Sringeri Sharada Peetham.</p>
        <p>The most important gap: systematic documentation of the thousands of small, living temples across rural India that contain unique architectural, inscriptional, and ritual traditions — before they are lost to development, neglect, or the homogenization of religious practice.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="special-section reveal">
      <h4 class="special-section-title">🔱 Rare Facts Most People Don't Know</h4>
      <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(300px, 1fr)); gap: 1.5rem; margin-top: 1rem;">
        <div style="padding: 1rem; border-left: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.7;"><strong style="color: var(--gold);">Tirupati Employs 18,000 People.</strong> The Tirupati Balaji temple (Tirumala) is the world's most visited religious site — surpassing the Vatican and Mecca — with over 50,000 daily visitors. Its annual income exceeds many Indian states' budgets.</div>
        <div style="padding: 1rem; border-left: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.7;"><strong style="color: var(--gold);">Brihadeeswarar's Paintings Were Lost & Found.</strong> The extraordinary Chola-era frescoes inside the Brihadeeswarar's circumambulatory passage were buried under later Nayak-era paintings for centuries. They were rediscovered in the 1930s and carefully restored — the only surviving large-scale Chola paintings.</div>
        <div style="padding: 1rem; border-left: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.7;"><strong style="color: var(--gold);">Kashi Is the World's Oldest Living City.</strong> Varanasi is documented as continuously inhabited since at least 3000 BCE — older than Rome, Athens, or Jerusalem. The Kashi Vishwanath has been worshipped at this location for over 3,000 years, through construction, destruction, and reconstruction.</div>
        <div style="padding: 1rem; border-left: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.7;"><strong style="color: var(--gold);">Angkor Wat Is a Hindu Temple.</strong> The largest religious monument on Earth — Angkor Wat in Cambodia — was built as a Vishnu temple by the Khmer Emperor Suryavarman II in the 12th century CE. It is oriented westward (unusual) — possibly because west is associated with Vishnu. Only later was it converted to Buddhist use.</div>
        <div style="padding: 1rem; border-left: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.7;"><strong style="color: var(--gold);">The Lingaraja Temple Has Never Been Entered by Non-Hindus.</strong> The Lingaraja Temple in Bhubaneswar, Odisha — one of the finest examples of Kalinga architecture — has a rule barring non-Hindus from entry. Lord Curzon was refused entry in 1903. The rule continues today.</div>
        <div style="padding: 1rem; border-left: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.7;"><strong style="color: var(--gold);">Adi Shankaracharya Established Four Monasteries at the Four Directions.</strong> The 8th-century philosopher-saint established Sringeri (south), Dwarka (west), Puri (east), and Badrinath (north) — matching the Char Dham pilgrimage circuit. These four mutts continue as the chief Advaita Vedanta institutions of Hinduism today.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
</HinduismLayout>

